						<summary>

						<p>Rock-cut well on the hill (north wall)</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">Chaṁḍasāti: Year 2: 210 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>This Prākrit inscription in Brāhmī characters of the third century A.D., furnishes the details of date viz., year 2, <hi rend="italic">ma</hi> 1, <hi rend="italic">he, pa</hi> 2, <hi rend="italic">di</hi> 1. These details correspond to December 210 A.D.</p>						

						<p>It refers to the reign of Chaṁḍasāti and records the establishment of the gift <hi rend="italic">(dhama)</hi> of a <hi rend="italic">khaṁgu</hi> (rock-cut well ?) by the minister Sasa of Khaḍḍavali.</p>						

						<p>Published in <hi rend="italic">Epigraphia Indica,</hi> Vol. XVIII, pp. 318. ff.</p>						

						</summary>
